			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024</a> paper:</span><br><i>Aconite: Towards Generating Sirius-Based Graphical Editors from Annotated Metamodels</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/NathanRichardson.html">Nathan Richardson</a>, <a href="../profile/DimitriosSKolovos.html">Dimitrios S. Kolovos</a>, <a href="../profile/AntonioGarcíaDomínguez.html">Antonio García-Domínguez</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3687997.3695642">10.1145/3687997.3695642</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It presents tooling to generate Sirius-based graphical editors automatically from annotated metamodels.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Editor generation is a vertical/generative process that derives concrete tooling artifacts from language models.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> The generated artifacts are graphical/diagrammatic editors, directly targeting visualization of DSL instances.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The approach targets metamodel-based DSLs whose editors are derived from their language definitions.
</li></ul></li></ul>
